792"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10760"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84811"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of sudden onset severe headache. The headache reached maximum intensity within seconds, involves his head and neck, and he describes it as the \u0027worst headache of his life\u0027. He experienced a similar but less severe episode three weeks ago. He reports nausea, dizziness and photophobia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of hypertension, chronic otitis media and complete heart block treated with a permanent pacemaker 30 years ago. His medications include amlodipine. He is a current smoker with a 40 pack-year history and does not drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed but is alert and oriented. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 180/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals no focal motor deficits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Formal cerebral angiography","Lumbar puncture","MRI brain","Non-contrast CT brain","Dix-Hallpike manoeuvre"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of subarachnoid haemorrhage including thunderclap headache, nausea, photophobia, and a possible sentinel bleed three weeks prior. Risk factors include hypertension and smoking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-contrast CT brain\u003C/strong\u003E is the investigation of choice for suspected subarachnoid haemorrhage within six hours of symptom onset, with sensitivity approaching 100%. CT angiography may then be performed to identify potential aneurysms if subarachnoid blood is detected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormal cerebral angiography\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure reserved for detailed aneurysm characterisation after subarachnoid haemorrhage has been confirmed, particularly when planning endovascular treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated 12 hours after headache onset if CT is negative but clinical suspicion remains high. Testing for xanthochromia can help differentiate true subarachnoid haemorrhage from a traumatic tap.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI brain\u003C/strong\u003E would be contraindicated in this patient due to his older model pacemaker. While some modern pacemakers are MRI-compatible, this requires specific confirmation from cardiology and radiology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDix-Hallpike manoeuvre\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose benign paroxysmal positional vertigo. While this patient has dizziness, the thunderclap headache mandates urgent investigation for subarachnoid haemorrhage first.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-contrast CT brain is the first-line investigation for suspected subarachnoid haemorrhage within six hours of headache onset.","A \u0027thunderclap headache\u0027 reaching maximum intensity within seconds warrants urgent investigation for subarachnoid haemorrhage.","A sentinel headache occurring weeks before a major subarachnoid haemorrhage occurs in up to 40% of cases."],"references":["Barritt A, Miller S, Davagnanam I, Matharu M. Rapid diagnosis vital in thunderclap headache. Practitioner. 2016 Apr;260(1792):23-8. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27337756/","Gorchynski J, Oman J, Newton T. Interpretation of traumatic lumbar punctures in the setting of possible subarachnoid hemorrhage: who can be safely discharged?. The California journal of emergency medicine. 2007 Feb;8(1):3. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2859734/","Radiology written report guideline, (short) version 5 (final). In: Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Radiologists (RANZCR) [online]. 2011. Available at: https://www.ranzcr.com/college/document-library/radiology-written-report-guideline"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69107"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"677"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69107"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-11T13:59:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-11T13:59:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"677"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84811"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"